  "method": "We propose Counterfactual Shortcut Breaking (CSB), a three-stage, modality-agnostic pipeline that discovers shortcut features, synthesizes calibrated counterfactuals that selectively toggle those features while holding causal evidence fixed, and trains with a paired invariance objective. Stage A (shortcut discovery) builds a candidate set of non-causal features at both the concept level and the input-variable level. For text, we prompt an LLM to annotate frequent, label-irrelevant concepts and compute a concept-bias score to rank candidates. For vision/VQA, we localize causal evidence using question-guided relevance maps to identify the pixels/patches that must be preserved, optionally supplemented with supervision from datasets that link questions/answers to exact segmentation masks. For generic inputs (including tabular), we run one-variable-at-a-time perturbation tests: ablate or randomize a single input dimension and measure whether the model’s decision changes while the ground-truth label remains; variables that cause decision flips without affecting the task semantics are marked as shortcut candidates.\n\nStage B (counterfactual synthesis) creates paired examples (x, x_cf) that differ only in suspected shortcuts. For text, we perform targeted rewriting that toggles a flagged concept’s presence/absence while constraining label consistency via an NLI check and a perplexity bound; we generate both removal and insertion variants to decorrelate concept and label. For images, we edit non-evidence regions: swap or restyle backgrounds, overlay distractor objects, or replace correlated context patches, while preserving the evidence mask at pixel level; for VQA this keeps the question-relevant region unchanged. For tabular, we resample shortcut columns conditionally from other records that share similar causal attributes but different shortcut values, or draw from an estimated p(feature | causal attributes). When historic logs contain natural interventions (e.g., the same item shown under different UIs/rankers), we harvest implicit counterfactuals by pairing the same content across contexts using assignment weights that balance exposure.\n\nTo make counterfactual severity uniform and training-stable, we calibrate each edit’s strength by matching a target logit KL-divergence between the model’s predictions on x and x_cf. Edits are iteratively adjusted (e.g., degree of style transfer, intensity of token rewrite, noise scale in tabular resampling) until the measured KL hits a prescribed band. We additionally support representation-space counterfactuals by intervening on internal features believed to encode shortcuts (e.g., zeroing or nudging specific features) while calibrating intervention strength via the same target KL, yielding activation-level counterfactuals when input edits are hard.\n\nStage C (invariance training) optimizes a paired objective on the counterfactual tuples: L = L_sup(x, y) + L_sup(x_cf, y) + λ KL(pθ(y | x) || pθ(y | x_cf)) + β ||φθ(x) − φθ(x_cf)||², where φθ is a mid-layer representation. We sample batches to balance concepts and shortcut values, prioritize concepts with high measured bias, and use a mild curriculum on the target-KL to progress from weak to stronger edits. Periodically, we refresh the shortcut set by rerunning discovery on the current model to chase newly emerged shortcuts. Evaluation reports both overall metrics and slice metrics by concept/shortcut presence to verify invariance.",
  "rationale": "Shortcut features are attractive to learners because they correlate with labels in the training distribution but are not invariant to interventions. By explicitly discovering such features and constructing counterfactual pairs that toggle only the shortcut while preserving causal evidence, we create supervision that directly penalizes shortcut reliance: the label is unchanged, yet the non-causal signal varies. The paired KL/feature-consistency losses make the model’s predictions and internal representations stable across these non-causal shifts, pushing learning toward features that remain predictive when shortcuts are broken.\n\nConcept-level discovery focuses counterfactual generation on high-impact, semantically meaningful shortcuts, while evidence localization in vision/VQA prevents label drift during image edits by holding the true visual cause fixed. Calibrating intervention strength with a target logit KL yields counterfactuals of comparable difficulty so training is neither dominated by trivial edits nor destabilized by extreme shifts. Together, these ingredients transform counterfactual data into an invariance-inducing curriculum that improves robustness under interventions.",
