  "method": "We propose C3: Causal-Consistent Counterfactuals. First, learn a factorized representation that separates causal content from shortcut cues. An encoder maps each input x to (z_c, z_s), where z_c is encouraged to be domain-invariant and label-predictive, and z_s captures environment/style/background factors. A decoder reconstructs x from (z_c, z_s). Training uses reconstruction, label prediction from z_c, an adversarial or divergence penalty that makes z_c uninformative about domain, and a complementary penalty that makes z_s predictable from domain. Cross-reconstruction is performed by swapping z_s between same-label pairs to force the decoder to render plausible variations of non-causal attributes while keeping causal structure intact.\n\nA counterfactual generator then produces interventions targeted at z_s. For each x, we either swap in a donor z_s from another cluster/domain or apply lightweight, pixel-level visual prompts that alter style, texture, color, or background while masking the object/causal region. The generator enforces cycle and region-preservation constraints (e.g., perceptual similarity within the masked causal region) and uses an external validator to accept counterfactuals only if causal content is preserved: for vision, a detector/segmenter checks object identity within the mask and a label-consistency check on the masked crop; for text, a task-specific verifier or entailment model ensures the label remains valid while style/register shifts.\n\nTraining the predictor with these counterfactuals couples three objectives: standard supervision on originals, a consistency objective that predictions match on x and its counterfactuals that differ only in z_s, and a worst-group optimization over pseudo-domains formed by clustering z_s or prompt styles to reduce reliance on any single shortcut. To make counterfactual mining efficient and targeted, we score examples and edits with a fast, single-pass uncertainty/abnormality head; samples with high confidence yet shortcut-aligned attributions or high post-edit uncertainty are prioritized. Their losses are upweighted via an uncertainty-guided moving average schedule so the model steadily focuses on the most spurious-sensitive cases without destabilizing training.\n\nWe apply a curriculum on intervention strength to avoid label leakage and preserve realism. Start with gentle z_s swaps or mild prompts (small color jitter, weak texture transfer, subtle background replacement) and gradually increase perturbation magnitude and diversity as the model becomes invariant. At inference, we can further stabilize predictions by marginalizing over z_s with a few fast augmentations or prompt variants that leave z_c intact, averaging logits to approximate the interventional prediction E[f(x) | do(z_s)].\n\nMonitoring includes interventional accuracy on counterfactuals, flip rate under z_s edits, invariance of intermediate features to z_s changes, and worst-group accuracy across z_s clusters. The pipeline is modality-agnostic: masks can be semantic segments in images, time–frequency masks in audio, or span masks in text; z_s-targeted edits become background replacement/style transfer, source remixing, or paraphrase style shifts, respectively.",
  "rationale": "Shortcuts arise when models exploit correlations carried by non-causal attributes. By explicitly disentangling a domain-invariant causal latent from a domain-specific shortcut latent, and then generating counterfactuals that intervene only on the shortcut latent, we create supervised interventional data where the label is fixed but spurious factors vary. Training with prediction consistency and worst-group optimization over these counterfactuals forces the model to discard information in z_s and rely on z_c.\n\nVisual prompts provide a practical, low-dimensional knob to edit non-causal attributes at scale, while an external validator avoids self-confirmation errors by ensuring that edits preserve causal content. Uncertainty-guided sampling concentrates counterfactual generation and training signal where the current model is most vulnerable to shortcuts, and the curriculum on edit strength maintains realism early while still breaking strong spurious cues later.",
